# 🛒 Multi-Level Market Basket Analysis using FP-Growth

## 🧠 The Problem

Standard Market Basket Analysis has a well-known weakness — **pattern explosion.**

When you run a traditional Apriori algorithm on a large retail dataset, you end up with thousands of hyper-specific rules like:

> *"Customers who buy a White Hanging Heart T-Light Holder also buy a White Metal Lantern."*

Technically correct. Strategically useless.

A business manager doesn't need to know which specific candle sells with which specific lantern. They need to know: **do customers who buy Home Decor also buy Kitchen products?** That's an insight you can actually act on — rearrange a store, launch a promotion, send a targeted email.

This project solves that problem by implementing **Multi-Level Mining with Concept Hierarchies** — a technique that lets us mine patterns at the category level instead of the item level, producing insights that are both statistically valid and business-actionable.

---

## 📦 The Dataset

**UCI Online Retail Dataset** — a real-world transactional record from a UK-based e-commerce retailer.

| Property | Value |
|----------|-------|
| Source | [UCI Machine Learning Repository](https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/352/online+retail) |
| Time Period | December 2010 — December 2011 |
| Raw Transactions | 541,909 |
| Countries | 38 |
| Unique Products | 3,877 |

> ⚠️ Dataset not included in this repo due to size. Download directly from the UCI link above.

---

## 🏗️ The Pipeline

This project follows a structured end-to-end pipeline — from raw noisy data to interactive business intelligence:

```
Raw CSV (541,909 rows)
        ↓
  Data Cleaning          → Remove nulls, cancellations, negatives
        ↓
  Concept Hierarchy      → Map 3,877 products into 8 categories
        ↓
  Binary Matrix          → One row per invoice, one column per category
        ↓
  FP-Growth Mining       → Extract frequent itemsets & association rules
        ↓
  MySQL Staging          → Store results in vortex_db
        ↓
  Visualization          → NetworkX graph + Power BI dashboard
```

