---

## 🧹 Data Cleaning

The raw dataset had several real-world quality issues that needed to be resolved before any mining could happen:

| Problem | Count | Action |
|---------|-------|--------|
| Missing CustomerID | 135,080 | Dropped — identity cannot be imputed |
| Cancelled transactions | 9,288 | Dropped — InvoiceNo starting with 'C' |
| Negative quantities | 10,624 | Dropped — returns and errors |
| Missing descriptions | 1,454 | Dropped — product unknown |

**Result: 397,884 clean transactions — ready for mining.**

> Why drop missing CustomerIDs instead of imputing? Because CustomerID is an identity, not a value. Without knowing *who* made the purchase, we can't group items into baskets. Imputing would create fake customers with random item combinations — corrupting every association rule downstream.

---

## 🗂️ Concept Hierarchy Construction

This is the core innovation of the project. Instead of mining at the item level, we first map every product into one of 8 business categories using keyword-based classification:

```python
def assign_category(description):
    desc = str(description).upper()
    if any(word in desc for word in ['CHRISTMAS', 'XMAS', 'SANTA']):
        return 'Christmas & Seasonal'
    elif any(word in desc for word in ['BAG', 'SHOPPER', 'TOTE']):
        return 'Bags & Storage'
    # ... and so on
```

**Final Category Distribution:**

| Category | Transactions | Share |
|----------|-------------|-------|
| Home Decor | 112,830 | 28.4% |
| Kitchen & Dining | 87,298 | 21.9% |
| Bags & Storage | 39,367 | 9.9% |
| Stationery & Craft | 32,142 | 8.1% |
| Christmas & Seasonal | 19,715 | 5.0% |
| Party & Celebrations | 18,166 | 4.6% |
| Garden | 15,721 | 4.0% |
| Toys & Novelty | 15,415 | 3.9% |

---

## ⛏️ FP-Growth Mining

With categories in place, we built a **binary transaction matrix** — one row per invoice, one column per category — and ran the FP-Growth algorithm.

**Why FP-Growth over Apriori?**
Apriori generates candidate itemsets at every pass — expensive on large datasets. FP-Growth builds a compressed tree structure once and mines it directly. No candidate generation means significantly faster execution on 397k rows.

**Parameters:**
- Minimum Support: 5% (rule must appear in at least 926 invoices)
- Minimum Lift: 1.0 (only genuine associations, not coincidences)

**Output:**
- 226 frequent itemsets discovered
- 56 simple association rules generated

---

## 📊 Key Findings

### Top Association Rules

| If Customer Buys... | They Also Buy... | Confidence | Lift |
|--------------------|-----------------|------------|------|
| Christmas & Seasonal | Toys & Novelty | 53% | 1.51 |
| Party & Celebrations | Garden | 55% | 1.41 |
| Stationery & Craft | Christmas & Seasonal | 66% | 1.41 |
| Garden | Party & Celebrations | 54% | 1.41 |
| Toys & Novelty | Stationery & Craft | 65% | 1.40 |

### What These Mean in Plain English

**🎄 Holiday Insight**
53% of customers who buy Christmas items also buy Toys & Novelty in the same transaction — 51% more often than random chance.
→ *Bundle Christmas and Toys sections together. Cross-promote in email campaigns.*

**🎉 Party Insight**
55% of Party shoppers also buy Garden products in the same transaction.
→ *Place seasonal garden items near party supplies. Target party buyers with garden promotions.*

**✏️ Craft Insight**
66% of Stationery & Craft buyers also buy Christmas items — the highest confidence rule discovered.
→ *Craft buyers are your best Christmas cross-sell target. Launch early Christmas campaigns for this segment.*

---

## 🕸️ Association Network Graph

The network below shows all 56 association rules. Each node is a category, each edge is a rule, and edge thickness represents lift strength.

![Association Network](association_network.png)

**Key observations:**
- Home Decor is the most connected node — it associates with almost every other category
- The Christmas ↔ Toys edge is the thickest — the strongest rule in the dataset
- Stationery & Craft sits centrally — a high-value cross-selling hub

